  <!-- 4.1 -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 01" label="Section 4.1" title="Sustainability in Municipal Administration" id="s-4-1">
    <p>In Switzerland, sustainability is a democratic effort driven by the 26 cantons and around 2,000 municipalities which each hold their own binding tools (Kammerer et al., 2023). The federal Energy Strategy 2050, locked in by referendum in 2017, sets the direction: phasing out nuclear, scaling up renewables, and capping per-capita primary energy (Notter, 2015; IEA, 2023). But most of the actual CO₂ cuts happen locally through building rules, procurement, and the way a municipality runs its own buildings.</p>
    <p>The key tool is the <em>Energiestadt</em> label which is the Swiss arm of the European Energy Award and has certified more than 460 municipalities since 1988, Oberägeri included (Trägerverein Energiestadt, 2020). The label audits six policy areas every four years and Gold requires that 75 % of measures are in place. Evaluations by the Swiss Federal Office of Energy show, even with causal isolation difficulties, that certified municipalities make more energy and climate conscious decisions compared to non-certified ones (Iten et al., 2004). The recent literature notes that municipal sustainability work in Switzerland has so far been mostly about energy efficiency, while adaptation and integrated planning still rely on a few pioneer actors rather than institutional capacity (Desthieux &amp; Joerin, 2022).</p>
  </Section>

  <!-- 4.2 -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 02" label="Section 4.2" title="Energy Efficiency in Public Buildings" id="s-4-2">
    <p>For public buildings in Switzerland, the legal framework is set by SIA 380/1, which defines maximum annual heat demand for new builds and renovations. These requirements are written into cantonal law through the <em>Mustervorschriften der Kantone im Energiebereich</em> (MuKEn), which has been adopted in full or in parts by all 26 cantons, Zug included (EnDK, 2018). Additional labels like Minergie are voluntary as they typically are more rigorous than the legal caps. When implemented, a Minergie retrofit can typically cut energy used for heating by around 70 % compared to a poorly insulated 1970s building (Le Guen et al., 2018).</p>
    <p>Unfortunately, buildings or stock built before 1980 still account for around 70 % of Swiss energy demand for heating (Streicher et al., 2018). Stock-flow modelling shows the federal 2050 carbon-neutrality target only work if envelope retrofits, renewable heating and rooftop PV are implemented simultaneously (Roca-Puigròs et al., 2020). Yet the only nation-wide econometric study of Swiss retrofits, has found that subsidized renovations actually deliver only 10–20 % energy savings on average which well below engineering predictions (Hondeborg et al., 2023). Any project-level scenario for the Rathaus has to account for that performance gap, with envelope U-values often two to three times above current MuKEn requirements (Streicher et al., 2018).</p>
  </Section>

  <!-- Visual break between sections -->
  <div class="section-banner reveal-fade">
    <img src="/oberaegeri-town.jpg" alt="Oberägeri town centre" />
  </div>

  <!-- 4.4 Solar Thermal -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 04" label="Section 4.4" title="Solar Thermal Energy" id="s-4-4">
    <p>Solar thermal systems convert sunlight directly into heat which can be used for hot water production or to supplement space heating. A typical system consists of collectors on the roof and a heat storage tank (Han et al., 2025). According to Swiss Solar (2026), a solar thermal system covers at least 30 % of the annual heat demand.</p>

    <h3>Collector categories</h3>
    <p>There are two main categories of solar thermal collectors: <strong>concentrating</strong> and <strong>non-concentrating</strong>. They differ in the temperatures they can achieve. Concentrating collectors, such as compound parabolic concentrators and parabolic troughs, reach very high temperatures and are mostly used in power plants. Non-concentrating collectors, such as flat-plate collectors and evacuated tube collectors, provide lower temperatures of 30–100 °C, which is sufficient for hot water and space heating in buildings (Omeiza et al., 2024). For our project, therefore, only the non-concentrating category is relevant, as the town hall primarily requires heat for hot water and heating.</p>

    <ul class="dashed">
      <li><strong>Flat-plate collector</strong> — solar radiation strikes a black-coated absorber surface, which absorbs the heat and transfers it to a storage tank via a heat-transfer fluid. A transparent glass cover lets solar radiation pass through but prevents convective and radiative heat loss to the outside (Omeiza et al., 2024).</li>
      <li><strong>Evacuated tube collector</strong> — operates on the same principle but encloses the absorber within two concentric glass tubes, with a vacuum between them. Since heat cannot cross a vacuum via convection, the vacuum acts as an effective insulation mechanism. As a result, this collector type operates more efficiently than the flat-plate collector even under cloudy skies and at low outdoor temperatures (Omeiza et al., 2024).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Advantages and disadvantages</h3>
    <ProConCards>
      <div class="pc-card pro">
        <h4>Advantages</h4>
        <p class="pc-sub">Emissions reduction</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Reduces GHG emissions by ≈ <strong>65 %</strong>, ozone depletion by <strong>69 %</strong>, and photochemical ozone formation by <strong>41 %</strong> compared with a gas-only heating system (Albertí et al., 2019).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">CO₂ savings potential</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Raising solar thermal share in Spain from 7.8 % to 30 % would save 1.24–1.64 Mt CO₂ annually (≈ 0.4–0.5 % of emissions).</li>
          <li>Potential is even higher in China (≈ 0.63 %) due to the coal-heavy electricity mix.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Energy conversion efficiency</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Achieves up to <strong>70 %</strong> energy-conversion efficiency (BBSR, 2024), versus ≈ 17 % for PV.</li>
          <li>Operating heat melts accumulated snow on collectors automatically — an advantage PV lacks (Omeiza et al., 2024).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="pc-card con">
        <h4>Disadvantages</h4>
        <p class="pc-sub">Long payback</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Averages 50.4 years due to high upfront costs and lower economic value of thermal energy vs. gas (Han et al., 2025).</li>
          <li>Context-dependent: Krawczyk et al. (2020) calculate 17–19 years for public buildings with higher hot-water demand.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Other environmental categories</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Production releases pollutants contributing to acidification (6 % worse) and eutrophication (61 % worse) vs. gas heating.</li>
          <li>Copper pipes, collectors and water tanks are the most problematic components (Albertí et al., 2019).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Corrosion risk</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Susceptible to corrosion in coastal or high-temperature environments; affects absorber surfaces, heat pipes and storage tanks.</li>
          <li>Aged heat-transfer fluids can release aggressive compounds, reducing efficiency and service life (Omeiza et al., 2024).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Climate dependence</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>A collector in Spain delivers three times as much energy as one in Poland; supplementary heating is often needed in winter (Krawczyk et al., 2020).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </ProConCards>
  </Section>

  <!-- 4.5 Photovoltaics -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 05" label="Section 4.5" title="Photovoltaics" id="s-4-5">
    <p>Photovoltaic Panels (PV) or Solar Panels are becoming a viable and cheap solution to transitioning to renewable energy production. PV panels can frequently be seen on roofs, building exteriors, or even on fields creating "solar farms".</p>
    <p>PV is a sustainable way of creating energy by using the photons naturally produced through the sun's rays and absorbing them for human consumption. PV panels require a semiconductor material to absorb the photon which dislodges electrons in the semiconductor material and creates electricity (U.S. Energy Information Administration (EIA), 2024). It is not certain that a photon will be absorbed by the material because photons can also be reflected or they can pass straight through the panel (U.S. Energy Information Administration (EIA), 2024). Most models, once they absorb the photon, have Watt capabilities ranging between 400–450 and total energy capacities ranging between 19–22 %. In a perfect scenario, a PV panel installed in optimal conditions in Swiss middle country can deliver about 1,000 kWh for every 1,000-watt panel (Swiss Solar Verband, n.d.).</p>

    <p>There are five categories of panels available on the market:</p>
    <ul class="dashed">
      <li><strong>Crystalline silicon cells</strong> — silicon panels in mono- or polycrystalline form. Monocrystalline use single-crystal silicon (highly efficient, more expensive); polycrystalline are made from multiple silicon cells (less efficient, cheaper). (Ali et al., 2025).</li>
      <li><strong>Single-junction</strong> — among the highest efficiencies on the market, very robust, mostly used for aerospace and military applications. (Papež et al., 2021).</li>
      <li><strong>Multijunction cells</strong> — use several semiconductor materials to capture a wider range of photons; more expensive to produce, very efficient. (Ali et al., 2025).</li>
      <li><strong>Thin films</strong> — thin semiconductor material laid on a substrate. Three key types: amorphous silicon (cheaper, less efficient than crystalline silicon); cadmium telluride (highly efficient, low cost); copper-indium-gallium-selenide (highly efficient with good low-light performance, but expensive materials). (Ali et al., 2025).</li>
      <li><strong>Emerging PV</strong> — new trials with organic materials or quantum-dot cells; experimental and not yet comparable to the other four categories. (National Laboratory of the Rockies, n.d.).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Advantages and disadvantages</h3>
    <ProConCards>
      <div class="pc-card pro">
        <h4>Advantages</h4>
        <p class="pc-sub">Energy Efficiency</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Current models reach 400–450 W and 19–22% efficiency. (Swiss Solar Verband, n.d.)</li>
          <li>In the Swiss midlands, a well placed 1000 W system yields ~1000 kWh annually. (Swiss Solar Verband, n.d.)</li>
          <li>Efficiency drops when panels are covered by snow, shade, or dirt.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Installation Factors</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Panels can be integrated into existing structures with minimal disruption.</li>
          <li>Multiple PV technologies allow cost &amp; performance optimization (crystalline silicon, thin films, multijunction, emerging PV, hybrids).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Recycling</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Switzerland has a dedicated recycling network (Sens e Recycling) (Swiss Solar Fachverband, n.d.).</li>
          <li>Panels have a long lifetime (~25 years) (Swiss Solar Verband, n.d.).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Environmental Impact</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>During sun collection the energy produced is completely carbon neutral and renewable.</li>
          <li>PV panels can provide a cheap and viable transition to renewable energy production.</li>
          <li>Can be installed on roofs, façades, or land, increasing design flexibility.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="pc-card con">
        <h4>Disadvantages</h4>
        <p class="pc-sub">Energy Efficiency</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Performance highly sensitive to placement, orientation, and cleanliness.</li>
          <li>Snow, shading, and debris reduce output.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Installation Factors</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Performance highly sensitive to placement, orientation, and cleanliness.</li>
          <li>Snow, shading, and debris reduce output.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Recycling</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Recycling systems in Germany are lacking (El Khawad et al., 2022).</li>
          <li>Panels are not designed for reuse, repair, or refurbishment (El Khawad et al., 2022).</li>
          <li>Recycling is energy intensive, loses material value, and does not recover all components (El Khawad et al., 2022).</li>
          <li>Broken solar cells pose risks during recycling (El Khawad et al., 2022).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Environmental Impact</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Production and recycling of panels is not carbon neutral as it requires certain rare materials or energy intensive materials (i.e. glass).</li>
          <li>Energy production depends on sunlight availability, shading, and weather conditions.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </ProConCards>
  </Section>

  <!-- 4.6 Emergency Power -->
  <Section chip="Chapter 04 / 06" label="Section 4.6" title="Emergency Power Systems" id="s-4-6">
    <p>The municipality must be able to operate 24 hours a day in crisis situations, which requires an on-site generator to ensure uninterrupted power. Oberägeri currently relies on a diesel generator for emergencies, but this system is neither carbon-reducing nor carbon-neutral. We therefore evaluated alternatives, including biofuel generators, biogas generators, and battery-powered (PV + battery) systems.</p>

    <h3>Biofuel and biogas generators</h3>
    <p>Biofuels are produced from <em>feedstock</em> — a term referring to biomass sources such as wood, ethanol and biodiesel (Clarence Lehman, 2026). Ethanol is made from fermented starch or sugar, while biodiesel is derived from oily plants like soybean. Because the carbon released during combustion is part of a short biological cycle, biofuels can reduce greenhouse-gas (GHG) emissions, although additional emissions occur during production and land-use processes (Clarence Lehman, 2026).</p>
    <p>Biogas generators run on biogas produced via anaerobic digestion and offer substantially lower life-cycle GHG emissions and reduced NOₓ and smoke compared with diesel (van den Oever et al., 2021; Nayak &amp; Sahoo, 2020). One study found a solar-biogas hybrid configuration to be the most feasible, with the lowest net present cost of $386,971, a cost of energy of $0.476/kWh, and CO₂ emissions of 10,346 kg/yr (Li et al., 2022). However, high annual maintenance costs of around $87,000 (Abdelhady, 2023), along with challenges such as gas cleaning, corrosion, and variable biogas availability, make biogas systems unsuitable for Oberägeri.</p>

    <div class="key-box">
      <p class="key-title">Key Considerations for Biofuel and Biogas Systems</p>
      <ul class="dashed">
        <li><strong>Environmental benefits</strong> — GHG reduction, improved local air quality, and reduced dependence on imported diesel through high substitution ratios of up to ≈ 80–85 % (Nayak &amp; Sahoo, 2020).</li>
        <li><strong>Operational challenges</strong> — high capital and O&amp;M costs, gas-cleaning requirements, corrosion risks, and variability in biogas production that can limit reliability.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Battery-powered (PV + battery) generators</h3>
    <p>Battery-powered generators rely on PV panels to produce electricity that is stored for emergency use, as described in section 4.5. A properly designed PV + battery system can achieve reliability comparable to diesel generators (Jurasz et al., 2020; Ali et al., 2023). Long-term performance, however, depends on solar variability, panel degradation and battery-capacity decline, requiring system oversizing to maintain <strong>95 % reliability after twenty years</strong> (Jurasz et al., 2020).</p>

    <h3>Diesel generators — the incumbent baseline</h3>
    <p>Diesel generators, while inexpensive to purchase, have high operating costs, a higher cost of energy, and approximately <strong>70 % higher CO₂ emissions</strong> than PV + battery alternatives (Ali et al., 2023; Felice et al., 2023). Their reliability also depends heavily on maintenance quality: well-maintained units have a <strong>20 % probability of failure within two weeks</strong> of operation, while poorly maintained units have a <strong>50 % probability of failure within the first 48 hours</strong> (Marqusee &amp; Jenket, 2020). Diesel fuel must also be replaced every 6–12 months to avoid bacterial contamination that can cause generator failure (Hwang et al., 2023).</p>
    <p>In contrast, PV/battery-powered systems provide near-instantaneous switchover within milliseconds (Sigenergy, 2025), compared with diesel's typical delay of more than ten seconds (Costa et al., 2023). They also enable significantly higher self-sufficiency — 96.83 % versus 39.15 % for diesel (Felice et al., 2023) — and offer greater adaptability to specific energy needs (Costa et al., 2023). Despite these advantages, the literature consistently identifies the high initial investment as the primary barrier to replacing diesel generators with PV/battery systems (Felice et al., 2023).</p>

    <h3>Diesel vs. PV + battery — comparison</h3>
    <ProConCards>
      <div class="pc-card pro">
        <h4>Advantages of PV + battery</h4>
        <p class="pc-sub">Near-instant response</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Switchover within milliseconds (Sigenergy, 2025), versus diesel's typical &gt;10 s delay (Costa et al., 2023).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Higher self-sufficiency</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>96.83 % self-sufficiency for PV + battery versus 39.15 % for diesel (Felice et al., 2023).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Lower emissions</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Roughly <strong>70 %</strong> lower CO₂ emissions than diesel (Ali et al., 2023; Felice et al., 2023), with no on-site combustion or fuel-transport footprint.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Customisable system design</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>PV array and battery sizing can be matched to the building's specific load and resilience targets (Costa et al., 2023).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="pc-card con">
        <h4>Limitations of diesel generators</h4>
        <p class="pc-sub">High emissions</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>On-site combustion releases CO₂, NOₓ and particulates, locked into a fossil-fuel supply chain (Ali et al., 2023).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Delayed response</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Start-up and synchronisation typically take &gt;10 seconds (Costa et al., 2023) — long enough to interrupt sensitive IT and communications equipment.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Fuel-degradation risks</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Stored diesel must be replaced every 6–12 months to prevent bacterial contamination that can cause generator failure (Hwang et al., 2023).</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="pc-sub">Maintenance-sensitive reliability</p>
        <ul class="pc-bullets">
          <li>Well-maintained units: 20 % failure probability within two weeks; poorly maintained: 50 % probability within 48 hours (Marqusee &amp; Jenket, 2020).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </ProConCards>
  </Section>

</Base>

<style>
  .toc{
    position:sticky;
    top:64px;
    z-index:50;
    background:rgba(250,250,247,0.92);
    backdrop-filter:saturate(180%) blur(12px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter:saturate(180%) blur(12px);
    border-bottom:1px solid var(--line);
  }
  .toc ul{
    display:flex;
    gap:clamp(16px, 3vw, 32px);
    list-style:none;
    margin:0;
    padding:14px 0;
    overflow-x:auto;
    -webkit-overflow-scrolling:touch;
  }
  .toc li{flex-shrink:0}
  .toc a{
    font-size:12px;
    letter-spacing:.06em;
    color:var(--ink-soft);
    white-space:nowrap;
    transition: color 0.2s var(--ease-out);
  }
  .toc a:hover{color:var(--moss)}

  .section-banner{
    width:100%;
    height:clamp(260px, 30vw, 420px);
    overflow:hidden;
  }
  .section-banner img{
    width:100%;
    height:100%;
    object-fit:cover;
    object-position:center 55%;
    transition:transform 0.6s var(--ease-out);
  }
  .section-banner:hover img{transform:scale(1.02)}

  /* Sub-headers inside ProConCards */
  :global(.pc-sub){
    font-size:11px !important;
    letter-spacing:.16em !important;
    text-transform:uppercase !important;
    color:var(--chip) !important;
    font-weight:600 !important;
    margin:14px 0 6px !important;
  }
  :global(.pc-card.pro .pc-sub){color:#4a7a55 !important}

  /* Bullet lists inside ProConCards */
  :global(.pc-bullets){
    list-style:none;
    padding:0;
    margin:0 0 10px;
  }
  :global(.pc-bullets li){
    font-size:16px;
    line-height:1.75;
    color:var(--ink-soft);
    padding:3px 0 3px 18px;
    position:relative;
  }
  :global(.pc-bullets li::before){
    content:"•";
    position:absolute;
    left:0;
    color:var(--chip);
  }
  :global(.pc-card.pro .pc-bullets li::before){color:#4a7a55}

  /* Key considerations box */
  .key-box{
    margin:24px 0;
    padding:20px 24px;
    border:1px solid var(--line);
    border-left:3px solid var(--chip);
    border-radius:2px;
    background:#fbfaf7;
    max-width:74ch;
  }
  .key-title{
    font-size:11px;
    letter-spacing:.18em;
    text-transform:uppercase;
    color:var(--chip);
    font-weight:600;
    margin:0 0 12px;
  }
  .key-box .dashed{margin:0}
</style>
